  "title": "Voluntary and open membership",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "92ec8802-06e1-4b86-b06e-d81df37a7898",
      "text": "The first of the Rochdale Principles states that co-operative societies must have an open and voluntary ([[wikt:voluntary]]) membership. According to the ICA's Statement on the Co-operative Identity, \"Co-operatives are voluntary organisations, open to all persons able to use their services and willing to accept the responsibilities of membership, without gender, social, racial, political or religious discrimination.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ecc2403d-7071-4975-a466-98c7d491ca61",
      "text": "# Anti-discrimination"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "51581e85-cb23-41bb-bcdd-b085bfb2a61a",
      "text": "To discriminate [[socially]] is to make a distinction between [[people]] on the basis of class ([[Social class]]) or category ([[Categorization]]). Examples of social discrimination include racial ([[racism]]), religious ([[Religious discrimination]]), sexual ([[Sexism]]), [[sexual orientation]], disability ([[Disability discrimination act]]), and ethnic ([[Ethnic persecution]]) discrimination.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "79f0ec2abfa9d2b7",
      "text": "To fulfil the first Rochdale Principle, a Co-operative society should not prevent anyone willing to participate from doing so on any of these grounds.  However, this does not prohibit the co-operative from setting reasonable and relevant ground rules for membership, such as residing in a specific geographic area or paying a membership fee to join, so long as all persons meeting such criteria are able to participate if they so choose."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "17a809e1-0db9-461a-bc00-ef22d8846c4b",
      "text": "# Motivations and rewards"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8a8e27a2-11b3-4c93-8eb7-edfe78362ccb",
      "text": "Given the voluntary nature of co-operatives, members need reasons to participate. Each person's motivations will be unique and will vary from one co-operative to another, but they will often be a combination of the following:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "20524198-88b7-416b-87e5-227d4f3499fd",
      "text": "- Financial: – Some co-operatives are able to provide members with financial benefits. \n- Quality of life – Serving the community through a co-operative because doing service makes one's own life better is perhaps the most significant motivation for volunteering. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c73795b1c168b5b3",
      "text": "Included here would be the benefits people get from being with other people, staying active, and above all having a sense of the value of ourselves in society that may not be as clear in other areas of life."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f57a7345-6bc6-4cf6-b011-521202188548",
      "text": "*Giving back&nbsp;– Many people have in some way benefited from the work of a co-operative and volunteer to give back."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c7da30a2-5856-42ea-a826-b1ec545a0a60",
      "text": "*Altruism&nbsp;– Some volunteer for the benefit of others."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b360fc2b-ebd9-425b-bf64-8b5ac3a34916",
      "text": "*A sense of duty&nbsp;– Some see participation in community as a responsibility that comes with citizenship. In this case, they may not describe themselves as volunteers."
    },
